78\n| ''[[Hawaii Five-O (1968 TV series)|Hawaii Five-O]]''\n| Nelson Bodine\n| Episode: \"A Stranger in His Grave\"\n|-\n| 1978\n| ''[[Little House on the Prairie (TV series)|Little House on the Prairie]]''\n| Sterling Murdock\n| Episode: \"Harriet's Happening\"\n|-\n| 1979\n| ''[[The Love Boat]]''\n| Ed Hartnett\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| 1979\n| ''[[Beane's of Boston]]''\n| John Peacock\n| Pilot\n|-\n| 1980\n| ''[[Soap (TV series)|Soap]]''\n| Minister\n| Episode: \"3.12\"\n|-\n| 1980\n| ''[[Young Maverick]]''\n| McBurney\n| Episode: \"Makin' Tracks\"\n|-\n| 1980\n| ''[[Hart to Hart]]''\n| Victor Sutter\n| Episode: \"Cruise At Your Own Risk\"\n|-\n| 1980\n| ''[[Tenspeed and Brown Shoe]]''\n| William Whitney\n| Episode: \"Diamonds Aren't Forever\"\n|-\n| 1980\n| ''[[Lou Grant (TV series)|Lou Grant]]''\n| Sturbridge\n| Episode: \"Pack\"\n|-\n| 1980\u20131988\n| ''[[Magnum, P.I.]]''\n| Jonathan Higgins\n| 158 episodes<br />[[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actor \u2013 Series, Miniseries or Television Film]]<br />[[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Drama Series]]<br />Nominated\u2014[[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actor \u2013 Series, Miniseries or Television Film]] <small>(1983, 1985, 1987\u20131988)</small><br />Nominated\u2014[[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Drama Series]] <small>(1984\u20131986)</small>\n|-\n|  1982\n| ''[[Tales of the Gold Monkey]]''\n| Monocle\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| 1982\n| ''[[Simon & Simon]]''\n| Jonathan Higgins\n| Episode: \"Emeralds Are Not a Girl's Best Friend\"\n|-\n| 1983\n| ''[[The Love Boat]]''\n| Manfred\n| Episode: \"The Last Case\"\n|-\n| 1986\n| ''[[Murder, She Wrote]]''\n| Jonathan Higgins\n| Episode: \"Magnum on Ice\"\n|-\n| 1987\n| ''Assault and Matrimony''\n| Neighbor, Cyril\n| Television film\n|-\n| 1989\n| ''[[Around the World in 80 Days (miniseries)|Around the World in 80 Days]]''\n| Sir Francis Commarty\n| 3 episodes\n|-\n| 1990\n| ''[[Hands of a Murderer]]''\n| Dr. John Watson\n| Television film\n|-\n| 1990\u20131991\n| ''[[The Hogan Family]]''\n| Lloyd Hogan\n| 13 episodes\n|-\n| 1992\n| ''[[Murder, She Wrote]]''\n| Edgar Greenstreet\n| Episode: \"Murder on Madison Avenue\"\n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year\n! Award\n! Nominated work\n! Result\n|-\n! colspan=4| [[Primetime Emmy Award]]s\n|-\n| [[36th Primetime Emmy Awards|1984]]\n| rowspan=4|[[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Drama Series|Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Drama Series]]\n| rowspan=4|''[[Magnum, P.I.]]''\n| {{nom}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emmys.com/awards/nominees-winners/1984|title=Nominees/Winners|date=1984|publisher=emmys.com|access-date=July 4, 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[37th Primetime Emmy Awards|1985]]\n| {{nom}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emmys.com/awards/nominees-winners/1985|title=Nominees/Winners|date=1985|publisher=emmys.com|access-date=July 4, 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[38th Primetime Emmy Awards|1986]]\n| {{nom}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emmys.com/awards/nominees-winners/1986|title=Nominees/Winners|date=1986|publisher=emmys.com|access-date=July 4, 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[39th Primetime Emmy Awards|1987]]\n| {{won}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emmys.com/awards/nominees-winners/1987|title=Nominees/Winners|date=1987|publisher=emmys.com|access-date=July 4, 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n! colspan=4| [[Golden Globe Award]]s\n|-\n| [[40th Golden Globe Awards|1982]]\n| rowspan=5| [[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actor \u2013 Series, Miniseries or Television Film|Best Supporting Actor \u2013 Series, Miniseries or Television Film]]\n|  rowspan=5|''[[Magnum, P.I.]]''\n| {{won}}<ref name=\"ggawards\">{{cite news|title=Winners and Nominees: John Hillerman|url=http://www.goldenglobes.com/person/john-hillerman|access-date=June 10, 2017|publisher=[[Golden Globe Awards]]|language=en}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[41st Golden Globe Awards|1983]]\n| {{nom}}<ref name=\"ggawards\" />\n|-\n| [[43rd Golden Globe Awards|1985]]\n| {{nom}}<ref name=\"ggawards\" />\n|-\n| [[45th Golden Globe Awards|1987]]\n| {{nom}}<ref name=\"ggawards\" />\n|-\n| [[46th Golden Globe Awards|1988]]\n| {{nom}}<ref name=\"ggawards\" />\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{IMDb name|384916}}\n* {{tcmdb name|id=86572|name=John Hillerman}}\n* {{IBDB name}}\n* {{iobdb name|28738|John Hillerman}}\n* [http://www.aveleyman.com/ActorCredit.aspx?ActorID=7990 John Hillerman] \u2014 Aveleyman\n\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Awards for John Hillerman\n| list =\n{{EmmyAward DramaSupportingActor}}\n{{GoldenGlobeSupportingActorTV}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hillerman, John}}\n[[Category:1932 births]]\n[[Category:2017 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male stage actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Texas]]\n[[Category:Outstanding Performance by a Supporting Actor in a Drama Series Primetime Emmy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Best Supporting Actor Golden Globe (television) winners]]\n[[Category:People from Denison, Texas]]\n[[Category:United States Air Force airmen]]\n[[Category:Moody College of Communication alumni]]\n[[Category:American people of German descent]]\n[[Category:American people of French descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Austrian descent]]\n[[Category:Male actors of German descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name       = John Hillerman\n| image      = John Hillerman Betty White The Betty White Show 1977 (cropped) 2.jpg\n| caption    = Hillerman in ''[[The Betty White Show]]'', 1977\n| birth_date  = {{birth date|1932|12|20}}\n| birth_place = [[Denison, Texas]], U.S.\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|2017|11|09|1932|12|20}}\n| death_place = [[Houston, Texas]], U.S.\n| birth_name  = John Benedict Hillerman\n| years_active = 1957\u20131999\n| alma_mater = [[University of Texas at Austin]]\n| occupation = Actor\n}}\n\n'''John Benedict Hillerman''' (December 20, 1932&nbsp;\u2013 November 9, 2017) was an American actor best known for his starring role as [[Jonathan Higgins|Jonathan Quayle Higgins III]] on the television series ''[[Magnum, P.I.]]'' that aired from 1980\u20131988. For his role as Higgins, Hillerman earned five [[Golden Globe Award|Golden Globe]] nominations, winning in 1981, and four [[Emmy Award|Emmy]] nominations, winning in 1987. He retired from acting in 1999.\n\n==Early life and career==\nHillerman was born in [[Denison, Texas]], the son of Christopher Benedict Hillerman, a gas station owner, and Lenora Joan (''n\u00e9e'' Medlinger).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/2/John-Hillerman.html|title=John Hillerman Biography|website=filmreference.com|access-date=July 4, 2014}}</ref> He was the middle child with two sisters.<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/11/09/obituaries/john-hillerman-who-played-snooty-sidekick-on-magnum-pi-dies-at-84.html|title=John Hillerman, Snooty Sidekick on 'Magnum, P.I.,' Dies at 84| newspaper=[[The New York Times]]| date=November 9, 2017| last=Haas| first=Matthew| accessdate=November 9, 2017}}</ref> His father was the grandson of immigrants from [[Germany]] and [[France]],<ref name=\"Sheff\">{{cite magazine| last=Sheff| first=David| url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20084770,00.html| title=The Lean Years Are Over for John Hillerman, Who's Finding a Magnum of Success in Hawaii| work=[[People (magazine)|People]]| date=April 18, 1983| access-date=July 4, 2014}}</ref> and his mother the daughter of immigrants from [[Austria]] and Germany.<ref name=\"Sheff\" /> Hillerman developed an interest in [[opera]] at the age of ten, and traveled to [[Dallas]] to watch [[Metropolitan Opera]] productions.<ref name=oc /> He attended St. Xavier's Academy,<ref name=oc /> and after graduation, he attended the [[University of Texas at Austin]] for three years, majoring in [[journalism]].<ref>{{cite news| last=Quttman|first=Monika| url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=861&dat=19870617&id=PZ5HAAAAIBAJ&sjid=fn8MAAAAIBAJ&pg=4979,2933505|title='Higgins' Not Really British| work=[[The Victoria Advocate]]| agency=[[Tribune Media Services]]| date=June 17, 1987| access-date=July 4, 2014}}</ref>\n\nHillerman served four years in the [[United States Air Force]] (1953-1957), working in maintenance in a [[Convair B-36 Peacemaker|B-36]] wing of the [[Strategic Air Command]], and achieving the rank of [[sergeant]].<ref name=oc /><ref name=\"Variety\">{{cite news| url=https://variety.com/2017/tv/obituaries-people-news/john-hillerman-dead-dies-magnum-p-i-1202611576/| title=John Hillerman, Emmy-Winning 'Magnum, P.I.' Actor, Dies at 84| newspaper=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]| access-date=November 9, 2017| date=November 9, 2017}}</ref> He became interested in acting after working with a [[Repertory theatre|theatrical group]] in [[Fort Worth, Texas|Fort Worth]] during his service: \"I was bored with barracks life. I got into [acting] to meet people in town. A light went on.\"<ref name=oc /> After his 1957 discharge, he moved to [[New York City]] to study at the [[American Theatre Wing]], and performed in professional theater for the next twelve years, in productions such as ''[[Henry IV, Part 2]]'' and ''[[The Great God Brown]]''.<ref>{{cite web| title=(\"John Hillerman\" search results)| url=http://www.playbill.com/searchpage/search?shows=on&people=on&theatres=on&q=John+Hillerman&qasset=00000150-ac85-d16d-a550-ecbfd4000003 |journal=[[Playbill]]| access-date=July 12, 2017|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20170712010040/http://www.playbill.com/searchpage/search?q=John%20Hillerman&shows=on&qasset=00000150-ac85-d16d-a550-ecbfd4000003&|archivedate=July 12, 2017|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Despite over 100 stage roles,<ref name=oc /> Hillerman was unable to make a living as a stage actor, and he moved to [[Hollywood]] in 1969.<ref name=\"oc\" /><ref name=\"Variety\" />\n\n==Career==\n=== Film ===\nHillerman made his film debut in ''[[They Call Me Mister Tibbs!]]'' (1970) in an uncredited role as a reporter.<ref name=\"TMZ\">{{cite news|url=http://www.tmz.com/2017/11/09/magnum-p-i-star-john-hillerman-dead/| title='Magnum, P.I.' Star John Hillerman Dead At 84| work=[[TMZ]]|access-date=November 9, 2017| date=November 9, 2017}}</ref> Director [[Peter Bogdanovich]], with whom Hillerman had previously worked during his stage career, cast Hillerman in his films ''[[The Last Picture Show]]'', ''[[What's Up, Doc? (1972 film)|What's Up, Doc?]]'', and ''[[Paper Moon (film)|Paper Moon]].''<ref name=\"oc\">{{cite news| last1=Logan| first1=Dan| title=John Hillerman Says Goodbye to Magnum, P.I.| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=92AEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA215&dq=%22John+Hillerman%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjM8MD9wYLVAhVr6IMKHcTsDXgQ6AEIRTAF#v=onepage&q=%22John%20Hillerman%22&f=false| access-date=July 12, 2017| work=Orange Coast| date=June 1988| pages=214\u2013215}}</ref> Hillerman worked steadily thereafter in motion pictures and television through the 1970s, including notable supporting roles in the 1974 films ''[[Chinatown (1974 film)|Chinatown]]'' and ''[[Blazing Saddles]]''.<ref name=\"NYT\" /> After being cast in ''[[Magnum, P.I.]]'', he shot only four additional pictures between 1980 and 1996, with his final film performance coming in ''[[A Very Brady Sequel]]''.\n\n=== Television ===\n[[File:Betty white show 1977.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Hillerman and [[Betty White]] in a 1977 publicity photo for ''[[The Betty White Show]]'']]\nIn 1975, Hillerman was a co-star in ''[[Ellery Queen (TV series)|Ellery Queen]]'' as Simon Brimmer, a radio [[detective]] who hosted a [[Radio programming|radio show]] and tried to outsmart the title character ([[Jim Hutton]]).{{r|etvs|page1=305}} From 1976\u20131980, he had a recurring role as Mr. Conners on the sitcom ''[[One Day at a Time (1975 TV series)|One Day at a Time]]'', and he co-starred as [[Betty White]]'s estranged husband on ''[[The Betty White Show]]'' (1977\u20131978).<ref name=\"etvs\">{{cite book| last1=Terrace| first1=Vincent| title=Encyclopedia of Television Shows, 1925 through 2010| date=2011| publisher=McFarland & Company, Inc., Publishers| location=Jefferson, N.C.| isbn=978-0-7864-6477-7| page=94|edition=2nd}}</ref> In 1978, Hillerman also appeared in an episode of ''[[Little House on the Prairie (TV series)|Little House on the Prairie]]'' called \"Harriet's Happenings\".\n\nHe is perhaps best remembered for his role as former [[British Army]] [[Regimental sergeant major|Sergeant Major]] [[Jonathan Higgins]] in ''[[Magnum, P.I.]]'' (1980\u20131988),{{r|etvs|page1=642}} for which he learned to speak in the educated middle/upper class English accent known as [[Received Pronunciation]], the King's or Queen's English by listening to a recording of [[Laurence Olivier]] reciting ''[[Hamlet (1948 film)|Hamlet]]''.<ref name=\"wp\">{{cite news| last1=Conroy| first1=Sarah Booth| title=John Hillerman| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/tv/1986/06/01/john-hillerman/ec984500-36d8-41ee-af33-3d9829b2191c/|access-date=July 12, 2017| work=The Washington Post| date=June 1, 1986| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170712013547/https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/tv/1986/06/01/john-hillerman/ec984500-36d8-41ee-af33-3d9829b2191c/?utm_term=.fa49385a0ec1|archivedate=July 12, 2017}}</ref><ref group=note>An article about Hillerman in ''[[Orange Coast (magazine)|Orange Coast]]'' magazine in June 1988 said, \"...&nbsp;the accent supplanted a thick drawl. Born and raised in Texas, he [Hillerman] trained away the drawl in a year of intensive work in New York's American Theatre Wing.\"</ref> He considered Higgins his favorite role,<ref name=\"latimes\" /> and described the character in a 1988 interview as \"think[ing] he's the only sane character [in the show], and everyone else is stark raving mad.\"<ref name=\"oc\" />\n\nIn 1982, Hillerman starred in the television pilot of ''[[Tales of the Gold Monkey]]'', as a German villain named Fritz the Monocle.<ref name=\"HRO\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/john-hillerman-dead-magnum-pi-actor-was-84-1056800| title=John Hillerman, Higgins on 'Magnum, P.I.,' Dies at 84| newspaper=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]| access-date=November 9, 2017| date=November 9, 2017| first=Mike| last=Barnes}}</ref> He hosted the 1984 [[David Hemmings]]-directed puzzle video ''[[Money Hunt: The Mystery of the Missing Link]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Billboard Videocassette Top 40|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Music/Archive-Billboard-IDX/IDX/80s/1984/BB-1984-09-15-OCR-Page-0030.pdf| access-date=July 12, 2017| work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]| date=September 15, 1984| page=30}}</ref> In 1990, Hillerman returned to television as Lloyd Hogan in the sixth and final season of the sitcom ''[[The Hogan Family]]''.{{r|etvs|page1=465}} That same year, he portrayed [[Dr. Watson]] to [[Edward Woodward]]'s [[Sherlock Holmes]] in ''[[Hands of a Murderer]]''.<ref name=\"HRO\" />\n\nIn 1993, he appeared in ''Berlin Break'' for one season.<ref name=\"wp\" /> He played the role of Mac MacKenzie, a former spy and currently the proprietor of Mac's, a bar in [[West Berlin]] considered to be neutral territory during the [[Cold War]].<ref name=\"etvs\" /> Mac teamed up with two jobless spies as investigators: Valentin Renko ([[Nicholas Clay]]), an ex-[[KGB]] agent, and Willy Richter ([[Kai Wulff]]), an ex-[[Federal Intelligence Service (Germany)|BND]] (West German secret service) operative.<ref name=\"Variety\" /> The show reunited him with [[Jeff MacKay]], who portrayed \"Mac\" MacReynolds in ''Magnum P.I.''.<ref name=\"Fox\">{{cite web| url=http://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/2017/11/09/magnum-p-higgins-actor-john-hillerman-dies-at-84.html| title='Magnum P.I.' Higgins actor John Hillerman dies at 84| publisher=[[Fox News]]| access-date=November 9, 2017| date=November 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Later years and death==\nAfter Hillerman retired from acting in 1999, he returned to his home state of Texas.<ref name=\"latimes\">{{cite web| url=http://www.latimes.com/local/obituaries/la-me-john-hillerman-20171109-story.html| title='Magnum, P.I.' actor John Hillerman dies at 84| newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]| date=November 9, 2017| access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref> On November 9, 2017, he died of [[cardiovascular disease]] at his [[Houston]] home, at the age of 84.<ref name=\"NYT\"/><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.tmz.com/2017/12/06/john-hillerman-magnum-pi-cause-of-death-heart-disease/| title='Magnum, P.I.' Star Died From Heart Disease| work=[[TMZ]]| date=December 7, 2017| accessdate=December 7, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\nSources:<ref name=\"Variety\" /><ref name=\"HRO\" /><ref name=\"Fox\" /><ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.fandango.com/people/john-hillerman-294613/film-credits| title=John Hillerman Filmography| publisher=FanDango| access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.hollywood.com/celebrities/john-hillerman-58907541/| title=John Hillerman| publisher=Hollywood|access-date=November 9, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/person/86572%7C0/John-Hillerman/filmography.html| title=John Hillerman Filmography| access-date=November 9, 2017| publisher=Turner Classic Movies}}</ref>\n<!--Sources Cover Film and Television Section---->\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n|-\n| 1970\n| ''[[They Call Me Mister Tibbs!]]''\n| Reporter\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 1971\n| ''[[Lawman (film)|Lawman]]''\n| Totts\n| \n|-\n| 1971\n| ''[[The Last Picture Show]]''\n| Teacher\n| \n|-\n| 1971\n| ''[[Honky (film)|Honky]]''\n|\n|\n|-\n| 1972\n| ''[[What's Up, Doc? (1972 film)|What's Up, Doc?]]''\n| Hotel Manager Kaltenborn\n| \n|-\n| 1972\n| ''[[The Carey Treatment]]''\n| Jenkins\n| \n|-\n| 1972\n| ''[[Skyjacked (film)|Skyjacked]]''\n| Walter Brandt\n| \n|-\n| 1972\n| ''[[The Outside Man]]''\n| Department Store Manager\n| \n|-\n| 1973\n| ''[[The Thief Who Came to Dinner]]''\n| Edmund Lasker\n| \n|-\n| 1973\n| ''[[High Plains Drifter]]''\n| Bootmaker\n| \n|-\n| 1973\n| ''[[Paper Moon (film)|Paper Moon]]''\n| Deputy Hardin / Jess Hardin\n|\n|-\n| 1973\n| ''[[The Naked Ape (film)|The Naked Ape]]''\n| Psychiatrist\n| \n|-\n| 1974\n| ''[[Blazing Saddles]]''\n| Howard Johnson\n| \n|-\n| 1974\n| ''[[The Nickel Ride]]''\n| Carl\n| \n|-\n| 1974\n| ''[[Chinatown (1974 film)|Chinatown]]''\n| Russ Yelburton\n| \n|-\n| 1975\n| ''[[At Long Last Love]]''\n| Rodney James\n| \n|-\n| 1975\n| ''[[The Day of the Locust (film)|The Day of the Locust]]''\n| Ned Grote\n| \n|-\n| 1975\n| ''[[Lucky Lady]]''\n| McTeague\n| \n|-\n| 1977\n| ''[[Audrey Rose (film)|Audrey Rose]]''\n| Scott Velie\n| \n|-\n| 1979\n| ''[[Sunburn (1979 film)|Sunburn]]''\n| Webb\n| \n|-\n| 1981\n|''[[History of the World, Part I]]''\n| Rich Man\n| (The French Revolution)\n|-\n| 1984\n| ''[[Up the Creek (1984 film)|Up the Creek]]''\n| Dean Burch\n| \n|-\n| 1989\n| ''[[Gummib\u00e4rchen k\u00fc\u00dft man nicht]]''\n| Padre\n| \n|-\n| 1996\n| ''[[A Very Brady Sequel]]''\n| Dr. Whitehead\n| (final film role)\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n|-\n| 1971\n| ''Sweet, Sweet Rachel''\n| Medical Examiner\n| Television film\n|-\n| 1972\n| ''[[The Sixth Sense (TV series)|The Sixth Sense]]''\n| Adrian Weems\n| Episode: \"Once Upon a Chilling\"\n|-\n| 1972\n| ''[[Mannix]]''\n| Larry Lawton\n| Episode: \"Light and Shadow\"\n|-\n| 1972\n| ''The Great Man's Whiskers''\n| Major Underwood\n| Television film\n|-\n| 1973\n| ''[[Mannix]]''\n| J. H. Morell\n| Episode: \"Silent Target\"\n|-\n| 1974\n| ''[[Maude (TV series)|Maude]]''\n| Drunk\n| Episode: \"The Commuter Station\"\n|-\n| 1974\n| ''[[Kojak]]''\