\n| rowspan=\"2\" {{n/a|Herself}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"6\"| 2019\n| [[MTV]] Push\n| Ones To Watch 2019\n| {{nom}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.co.uk/mtv-push-ones-to-watch-2019/news/voting-for-mtv-push-ones-to-watch-2019-is-open|title=voting for mtv push: ones to watch 2019 is open!|publisher=[[MTV]]|date=14 January 2019|accessdate=16 January 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| Radio X\n| Best of British 2019\n| \"Uh-Huh\"\n| {{nom|#84}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://charts.radiox.co.uk/2019/|title=Best of British 2019|publisher=Radio X|accessdate=25 April 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Americana Music Honors & Awards]]\n| Emerging Act of the Year\n| {{n/a|Herself}}\n| rowspan=\"3\" {{nom}}<br/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://americanamusic.org/news/americana-announces-its-2019-honors-awards-nominees|title=Americana announces its 2019 honors & awards nominees|publisher=[[Americana Music Honors & Awards]]|date=14 May 2019|accessdate=1 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://completemusicupdate.com/article/aim-announces-2019-independent-music-awards-nominees/|title=AIM announces 2019 Independent Music Awards nominees|publisher=[[Association of Independent Music]]|date=24 July 2019|accessdate=1 August 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=3|[[Association of Independent Music|AIM Independent Music Awards]]\n| Best Independent Album\n| ''Jade Bird''\n|-\n| UK Independent Breakthrough \n| rowspan=5 {{n/a|Herself}}\n|-\n| International Breakthrough\n| {{won}}<ref>https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/8529026/aim-independent-music-awards-winners-list</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=3|2020\n|[[Gaffa (magazine)|Denmark GAFFA Awards]]\n| Best Foreign New Artist\n| {{pending}}<ref>https://gaffa.dk/prisen/afstemningen</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=2|[[NME Awards]]\n| Best New Act in the World\n| rowspan=2 {{nom}}<ref>https://www.nme.com/awards/winners</ref>\n|-\n| Best British New Act\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Jade Bird (musician)|Jade Bird}}\n*[http://www.jade-bird.com Official website]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bird, Jade}}\n[[Category:1997 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century English singers]]\n[[Category:British singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Military brats]]\n[[Category:People from Northumberland]]\n[[Category:21st-century English women singers]]\n[[Category:Bibliophiles]]\n", "name_user": "81.105.212.98", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eEarly life)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jade_Bird"}
{"title_page": "WJBF", "text_new": "{{Infobox broadcast\n|  call_letters             = WJBF\n|  city                     = \n|  station_logo             = [[Image:Wjbf 2010.png|200px]]\n----\n[[File:Wjbf dt2.png|175px]]\n|  station_slogan           = ''Coverage You Can Count On''\n|  station_branding         = ''WJBF NewsChannel 6''\n|  digital                  = 28 ([[ultra high frequency|UHF]])\n|  virtual                  = 6 ([[Program and System Information Protocol|PSIP]])\n|  subchannels              = \n|  other_chs                = \n|  affiliations             = {{ubl|'''6.1:''' [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] (secondary until 1967)|'''6.2:''' [[MeTV]]|'''6.3:''' [[Ion Television]]|'''6.4:''' [[Court TV Mystery]]}}\n|  owner                    = [[Nexstar Media Group]]\n|  licensee                 = Nexstar Broadcasting, Inc.\n|  location                 = [[Augusta, Georgia]]\n|  country                  = [[United States]]\n|  founded                  = \n|  airdate                  = {{Start date and age|1953|11|23|p=y}}\n|  enddate                  = \n|  callsign_meaning         = [[J. B. Fuqua|'''J'''ohn '''B'''rooks '''F'''uqua]]<br>''(founder of the station)''\n|  sister_stations          = \n|  former_callsigns         =\n|  former_channel_numbers   = '''[[analog television|Analog]]:'''<br>6 ([[Very high frequency|VHF]], 1953\u20132009)\n|  former_affiliations      = {{ubl|[[NBC]] (1953\u20131974; secondary from 1967)|[[CBS]] (secondary, 1953\u20131954)|[[DuMont Television Network|DuMont]] (secondary, 1953\u20131956)}}\n|  effective_radiated_power = 1000 [[kilowatt|kW]]<br>755 kW ([[construction permit|CP]])\n|  HAAT                     = {{convert|507|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}<br>{{convert|504.4|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} (CP)\n|  facility_id              = 27140\n|  coordinates              = {{nowrap|{{coord|33|24|20.7|N|81|50|0.5|W|type:landmark_scale:2000}}}}\n|  licensing_authority      = [[Federal Communications Commission|FCC]]\n|  homepage                 = {{URL|https://www.wjbf.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''WJBF''', [[virtual channel]] 6 ([[ultra high frequency|UHF]] [[digital terrestrial television|digital]] channel 28), is an [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]-[[network affiliate|affiliated]] [[television station]] [[city of license|licensed]] to [[Augusta, Georgia]], United States. The station is owned by [[Nexstar Media Group]]. WJBF's studios are located in Television Park, near the Augusta West Mall in Augusta; and its transmitter is located in [[Beech Island, South Carolina]].\n\n==History==\nWJBF-TV began operations on November 23, 1953 as Augusta's first television station.<ref>[http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/Archive-BC-IDX/53-OCR/BC-1953-11-30-OCR-Page-0068.pdf \"Seven new TV outlets go on the air.\"]{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} ''[[Broadcasting and Cable|Broadcasting - Telecasting]]'', November 30, 1953, pg. 68.</ref> The station was founded by the Georgia-Carolina Broadcasting Company, the broadcasting arm of local entrepreneur [[J. B. Fuqua]],<ref>[http://www.georgiaencyclopedia.org/nge/Article.jsp?id=h-1914]</ref> who also owned [[NBC Radio Network]] affiliate WJBF (1230 AM). WJBF-TV was a primary [[NBC]] affiliate, but picked up programs from [[CBS]], ABC and [[DuMont Television Network|DuMont]] on a secondary basis. Sister station WJBF radio was sold by Fuqua in 1954 (it is now [[WEZO]]).<ref>[http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/Archive-BC-IDX/54-OCR/1954-07-05-BC-OCR-Page-0066.pdf \"Fountain firm buys WJBF for $125,000.\"]{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} ''Broadcasting - Telecasting'', July 5, 1954, pg. 66.</ref> It lost CBS only three months later when [[WRDW-TV]] (channel 12) signed on.\n\nOn September 1, 1967 WJBF became a primary ABC affiliate.<ref>\"WJBF (TV) goes primary ABC.\" ''Broadcasting'', August 14, 1967, pg. 52. [http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-IDX/67-OCR/1967-08-14-BC-0052.pdf] {{dead link|date=June 2014}}</ref> The move relegated NBC to a shared secondary affiliation with WRDW-TV. This was an unusual situation for a then two-station market, especially one as small as Augusta. ABC, as the smallest and weakest of the big three networks, would not be on nearly the same footing with CBS and NBC until the 1970s, when most markets of Augusta's size grew large enough to support three full network affiliates. However, fellow NBC affiliate [[WIS-TV]] in [[Columbia, South Carolina|Columbia]] provided at least grade B coverage to the South Carolina side of the market. In contrast, no full-time ABC affiliate put even a grade B signal into the area. Fuqua reasoned that if channel 6 took a primary ABC affiliation, it wouldn't have significant out-of-market competition.  Additionally, in 1966 Fuqua bought two full-time ABC affiliates, [[WTVW]] in [[Evansville, Indiana]] and KTHI-TV (now [[KVLY-TV]]) in [[Fargo, North Dakota]], and apparently wanted to get his other stations\u2014WJBF and [[KTVE]] in [[El Dorado, Arkansas]]\u2014in line with the new acquisitions. In 1969, Fuqua branched out into the movie theater business when he purchased Martin Theaters of Georgia, forerunner of [[Carmike Cinemas]]. At the time, Martin Theaters of Georgia itself also owned [[WTVM]] in [[Columbus, Georgia]], and [[WTVC]] in [[Chattanooga, Tennessee]], also ABC affiliates.  Those were added to Fuqua's portfolio.\n\nWhen WATU (channel 26, later WAGT) began operations in December 1968, conventional wisdom suggested that it would become a full NBC affiliate. However, since many Augusta viewers still didn't have UHF-capable sets, NBC allowed WJBF and WRDW-TV to continue to cherry-pick most of its stronger programs.  For its part, WJBF kept airing both the ''[[Today (American TV program)|Today Show]]'' and ''[[The Tonight Show]]'', which preempted ABC's ''[[The Dick Cavett Show]]'' among others. WATU was thus saddled with NBC's weaker programs, a major factor in the station going dark in 1970.<ref>\"One (network) to a customer.\" ''Broadcasting'', March 29, 1971, pg. 67. [http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-IDX/71-OCR/1971-03-29-BC-0068.pdf] {{dead link|date=June 2014}}</ref> When WATU returned to the air in 1974 as a full-time NBC affiliate, WJBF was forced to drop NBC programming once and for all, per an FCC order issued in 1971 that required VHF stations in markets with three or more commercial outlets to affiliate with only one network.\n\nFuqua began breaking up his business empire in 1980. His television stations were among the first assets to be sold, with WJBF and WTVM going to [[Missoula, Montana]]-based Western Broadcasting Company.<ref>[http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-IDX/80-OCR/1980-07-28-BC-OCR-Page-82.pdf]{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}[http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-IDX/80-OCR/1980-07-28-BC-OCR-Page-83.pdf \"Changing Hands.\" ''Broadcasting'', July 28, 1980, pp. 82-83]{{dead link|date=June 2014 }}</ref>, and WTVC going to the [[A. H. Belo Corporation]] of Dallas, Texas.   In 1984, Western sold its broadcast holdings to the [[Pearson Scott Foresman|SFN Companies]], then-parent of educational publisher [[Scott Foresman|Scott, Foresman and Company]].<ref>[http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-IDX/84-OCR/BC-1984-01-16-Page-0041.pdf \"Western sale.\" ''Broadcasting'', January 16, 1984, pg. 41] {{dead link|date=June 2014}}</ref> In 1986, SFN was sold to Pegasus Broadcasting, a new firm formed by members of SFN's management.<ref>[http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-IDX/86-OCR/BC-1986-07-14-Page-0066.pdf \"Changing hands.\" ''Broadcasting'', July 14, 1986, pg. 66] {{dead link|date=June 2014}}</ref> Spartan Radiocasting of [[Spartanburg, South Carolina]] purchased the station in 1992. Spartan was renamed [[Spartan Communications]] in 1995. Spartan merged with current owner [[Media General]] in 2000.\n\nWJBF replaced RTV with [[MeTV]] on digital subchannel 6.2 on September 26, 2011, as part of a groupwide affiliation agreement with Media General; the channel replaced RTV on some Media General-owned stations in other market.<ref>[http://www.tvnewscheck.com/article/2011/09/15/54029/metv-beefs-up-roster-with-10-new-stations Me-TV Beefs Up Roster With 10 New Stations] ''TVNewsCheck'', September 15, 2011.</ref>\n\n=== Augusta West, management of WAGT ===\n[[File:TV Networks in the former Barnes & Noble Augusta GA.jpg|thumb|left|The exterior of the new Television Park at Augusta West.]]\nIn October 2009, [[Schurz Communications]] announced that it would enter into joint sales and [[shared services agreement]]s with WJBF, meaning that [[WAGT (TV)|WAGT]]'s news operation and advertising sales department would be taken over by Media General. Most of WAGT's managerial staff were dismissed, and other employees were reassigned to different positions.<ref>{{cite news|last=Emerson|first=LaTina|title=WJBF, WAGT still negotiating with on-air personnel|url=http://chronicle.augusta.com/stories/2009/12/30/bus_561276.shtml|work=[[The Augusta Chronicle]]|date=December 30, 2009|accessdate=December 5, 2010}}</ref>\n\nMedia General had initially intended to move WAGT into an expanded wing of the WJBF building in downtown Augusta. Both WJBF and WAGT have had a longstanding presence in the downtown area. Channel 6's facility on Reynolds Street was built around 1956, and channel 26 moved into its Broad Street building, a converted theatre, in 1981. However, it soon became apparent that WJBF's facility could not sustain the expansion necessary to house both stations.  Media General instead chose to remodel what had been a [[big-box store]] to contain the stations. The new facility, located at the Augusta West Shopping Center in a former [[Barnes & Noble]] retail location, was opened in October 2011.<ref>{{cite news|last=Emerson|first=LaTina|title=WBBQ, other stations to move to new locations|url=http://chronicle.augusta.com/news/metro/2010-12-02/wbbq-other-stations-move-new-locations?v=1291282932|work=[[The Augusta Chronicle]]|date=December 2, 2010|accessdate=December 5, 2010}}</ref> While the two stations shared some internal services, WAGT's news operation and sales department operated autonomously from that of WJBF, and the two stations also produced competing news programming from their dedicated areas of the facility.<ref name=\"tvnc-wagtstudio\">{{cite web|title=Facility Helps Duop TVs Keep Own Identities|url=http://www.tvnewscheck.com/article/61044/facility-helps-duop-tvs-keep-own-identities|author=Arthur Greenwald|work=TVNewsCheck|publisher=NewsCheckMedia|date=July 26, 2012|accessdate=September 11, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe SSA was disbanded on February 16, 2016 after the acquisition of WAGT by [[Gray Television]], owner of [[WRDW-TV]].<ref name=\"gray-wagt\">{{cite web|title=Gray Television and WRDW News 12 Welcome WAGT NBC 26|url=http://www.wrdw.com/home/headlines/Gray-Television-and-WRDW-News-12-Welcome-WAGT-NBC-26-365796691.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160217092451/http://www.wrdw.com/home/headlines/Gray-Television-and-WRDW-News-12-Welcome-WAGT-NBC-26-365796691.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=17 February 2016|website=WRDW.com|publisher=Gray Television|accessdate=16 February 2016}}</ref> Gray accused Media General of \"[refusing] to agree to a smooth transition of personnel [from WAGT]\" and not allowing them to move along to the station's new owner, as they fell under the employment of WJBF due to the shared services agreement.<ref name=\"tvspy-blames\">{{cite web|title=Gray Blames Media General for Possible Job Losses at Augusta Station|url=http://www.adweek.com/tvspy/gray-blames-media-general-for-possible-job-losses-at-augusta-station/164035#.VsOdRLijBd0.mailto|website=TVSpy.com|accessdate=17 February 2016}}</ref> On February 26, 2016, an [[injunction]] was granted against Gray by Media General, claiming that Gray violated the SSA by unwinding it following its purchase of WAGT. The agreement was to last through 2020, and stipulated that all future owners of the station would remain subject to it.<ref name=\"chron-injunction\">{{cite news|title=Judge grants injunction halting WAGT sale|url=http://chronicle.augusta.com/news/business/2016-02-26/judge-grants-injunction-halting-wagt-sale|accessdate=February 27, 2016|work=The Augusta Chronicle|date=February 26, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Digital channels==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Channel\n! [[Video resolution|Video]]\n! [[Aspect ratio|Aspect]]\n! PSIP short name\n! Programming\n|-\n| 6.1 || [[1080i]] || rowspan=\"3\"|[[16:9]] || WJBF-HD || Main WJBF programming / [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] \n|-\n| 6.2 || [[720p]] || MeTV || [[MeTV]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www2.wjbf.com/entertainment/on_wjbf_tv/ |title=WJBF website TV listings |access-date=June 30, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110609075423/http://www2.wjbf.com/entertainment/on_wjbf_tv/ |archive-date=June 9, 2011 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n|-\n| 6.3 || rowspan=\"2\"|[[480i]] || ION || [[Ion Television]]\n|-\n| 6.4 || [[4:3]] || || [[Court TV Mystery]]\n|}\n\n==Local programming==\nSince 1954, WJBF has produced and aired the Sunday morning [[gospel music]] program ''Parade of Quartets'', one of the longest-running local programs of any kind on American television. The program has been a showcase for regionally and nationally known African-American gospel performers, and has also featured appearances from political and social figures. Augusta native [[James Brown]], [[Shirley Caesar]], [[Al Green]], the [[Mighty Clouds of Joy]], [[Dorothy Norwood]] and [[Jesse Jackson]] are among those who have appeared on the program.\n\nThe station also produces an [[urban music]] video program, ''Power Hitz'', which airs on Sunday evenings. ''Power Hitz'' has been on the air since 2001.<ref>{{cite news|last=DeMao|first=Alisa|title=Radio personalities add camera to mike|url=http://chronicle.augusta.com/stories/2001/09/13/ent_319380.shtml|work=[[The Augusta Chronicle]]|date=September 13, 2001|accessdate=December 5, 2010}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1954 until 1992, WJBF produced and aired a Sunday afternoon [[Southern gospel]] program featuring the locally based [[The Lewis Family]], known as the \"First Family of Bluegrass Gospel,\" that was seen in other markets via [[broadcast syndication|syndication]]. After the weekly series ended, WJBF continued to produce and air a yearly [[Christmas]] special until the group's retirement in 2009.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://thelewisfamilymusic.com|title=Home Page|website=thelewisfamilymusic|language=en-US|access-date=2018-07-06}}</ref>\n\n==News operation==\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Wjbf open 2010.png|thumb|right|The WJBF news open seen nightly at 6.{{deletable image-caption|Thursday, 31 March 2016}}]] -->\nAppropriately for being the first television station in the area, WJBF has led the ratings for most of its history, with rival WRDW-TV usually the runner-up. In recent years, WJBF and WRDW-TV had usually traded first and second place, while WAGT almost always placed third.\n\nIn the 1980s, its newscasts were branded ''[[NewsWatch (branding)|NewsWatch]] 6''. After being acquired by Spartan Radiocasting in 1992, WJBF and some other stations acquired by the company changed their branding to ''NewsChannel''. This station and most of its sister affiliates still use this branding today after being acquired by Media General. However, long after Spartan bought the station, WJBF retained the \"groovy 6\" logo it had used in one form or another since the late 1970s. This changed in 2002, when it adopted the \"arc\" logo used by most Media General stations.\n\nIn the 1990s, WJBF reached an agreement with the [[Augusta Mall]] to run a [[closed-circuit television|closed-circuit]] \"Mall TV\" feed on television screens throughout the mall featuring the day's news and coverage of some local special events. WJBF operated this service until the late-1990s. They also had a local agreement with Comcast to air a rebroadcast of the 6 p.m. show on the cable provider's channel 66. This arrangement ended in 2004 with the launch of a nightly 10 o'clock newscast on [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] affiliate [[WFXG]] (channel 54). The production uses different graphics and duratrans concealing the WJBF logos. The launch came after its studios were renovated.\n\nIn December 2009, WAGT and WJBF partnered under a shared services agreement, with WJBF producing WAGT's news, sales, and other programming. Schurz Communications still owns WAGT in part. Current WJBF reporter Paige Tucker is the face of WAGT's 6, 7, and 11pm newscasts.\n\nOn October 17, 2011, WJBF launched local newscasts in high definition starting with the morning newscast. It is the third station in the area to do so behind WFXG and WRDW-TV.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|https://www.wjbf.com/}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20101127154038/http://paradeofquartets.com/main/ ''Parade of Quartets'' website]\n*{{TVQ|WJBF}}\n\n{{Augusta TV}}\n{{ABC Georgia}}\n{{NXST TV}}\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2012}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wjbf}}\n[[Category:ABC network affiliates]]\n[[Category:Television stations in Augusta, Georgia|JBF]]\n[[Category:Television channels and stations established in 1953]]\n[[Category:1953 establishments in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:MeTV affiliates]]\n[[Category:Ion Television subchannel-only affiliates]]\n[[Category:Court TV Mystery affiliates]]\n[[Category:Prime Time Entertainment Network]]\n[[Category:Nexstar Media Group]]\n[[Category:Atlantic Coast Conference broadcasters]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox broadcast\n|  call_letters             = WJBF\n|  city                     = \n|  station_logo             = [[Image:Wjbf 2010.png|200px]]\n----\n[[File:Wjbf dt2.png|175px]]\n|  station_slogan           = ''Coverage You Can Count On''\n|  station_branding         = ''WJBF NewsChannel 6''\n|  digital                  = 42 ([[ultra high frequency|UHF]])<br>''(to move to 28 (UHF))''\n|  virtual                  = 6 ([[Program and System Information Protocol|PSIP]])\n|  subchannels              = \n|  other_chs                = \n|  affiliations             = {{ubl|'''6.1:''' [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] (secondary until 1967)|'''6.2:''' [[MeTV]]|'''6.3:''' [[Ion Television]]|'''6.4:''' [[Court TV Mystery]]}}\n|  owner                    = [[Nexstar Media Group]]\n|  licensee                 = Nexstar Broadcasting, Inc.\n|  location                 = [[Augusta, Georgia]]\n|  country                  = [[United States]]\n|  founded                  = \n|  airdate                  = {{Start date and age|1953|11|23|p=y}}\n|  enddate                  = \n|  callsign_meaning         = [[J. B. Fuqua|'''J'''ohn '''B'''rooks '''F'''uqua]]<br>''(founder of the station)''\n|  sister_stations          = \n|  former_callsigns         =\n|  former_channel_numbers   = '''[[analog television|Analog]]:'''<br>6 ([[Very high frequency|VHF]], 1953\u20132009)\n|  former_affiliations      = {{ubl|[[NBC]] (1953\u20131974; secondary from 1967)|[[CBS]] (secondary, 1953\u20131954)|[[DuMont Television Network|DuMont]] (secondary, 1953\u20131956)}}\n|  effective_radiated_power = 1000 [[kilowatt|kW]]<br>755 kW ([[construction permit|CP]])\n|  HAAT                     = {{convert|507|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}<br>{{convert|504.4|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} (CP)\n|  facility_id              = 27140\n|  coordinates              = {{nowrap|{{coord|33|24|20.7|N|81|50|0.5|W|type:landmark_scale:2000}}}}\n|  licensing_authority      = [[Federal Communications Commission|FCC]]\n|  homepage                 = {{URL|https://www.wjbf.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''WJBF''', [[virtual channel]] 6 ([[ultra high frequency|UHF]] [[digital terrestrial television|digital]] channel 42), is an [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]-[[network affiliate|affiliated]] [[television station]] [[city of license|licensed]] to [[Augusta, Georgia]], United States. The station is owned by [[Nexstar Media Group]]. WJBF's studios are located in Television Park, near the Augusta West Mall in Augusta; and its transmitter is located in [[Beech Island, South Carolina]].\n\n==History==\nWJBF-TV began operations on November 23, 1953 as Augusta's first television station.<ref>[http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/Archive-BC-IDX/53-OCR/BC-1953-11-30-OCR-Page-0068.pdf \"Seven new TV outlets go on the air.\"]{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} ''[[Broadcasting and Cable|Broadcasting - Telecasting]]'', November 30, 1953, pg. 68.</ref> The station was founded by the Georgia-Carolina Broadcasting Company, the broadcasting arm of local entrepreneur [[J. B. Fuqua]],<ref>[http://www.georgiaencyclopedia.org/nge/Article.jsp?id=h-1914]</ref> who also owned [[NBC Radio Network]] affiliate WJBF (1230 AM). WJBF-TV was a primary [[NBC]] affiliate, but picked up programs from [[CBS]], ABC and [[DuMont Television Network|DuMont]] on a secondary basis. Sister station WJBF radio was sold by Fuqua in 1954 (it is now [[WEZO]]).<ref>[http://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/Archive-BC-IDX/54-OCR/1954-07-05-BC-OCR-Page-0066.pdf \"Fountain firm buys WJBF for $125,000.\"]{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} ''Broadcasting - Telecasting'', July 5, 1954, pg. 66.</ref> It lost CBS only three months later when [[WRDW-TV]] (channel 12) signed on.\n\nOn September 1, 1967 WJBF became a primary ABC affiliate.<ref>\"WJBF (TV) goes primary ABC.\" ''Broadcasting'', August 14, 1967, pg. 52. [http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-IDX/67-OCR/1967-08-14-BC-0052.pdf] {{dead link|date=June 2014}}</ref> The move relegated NBC to a shared secondary affiliation with WRDW-TV. This was an unusual situation for a then two-station market, especially one as small as Augusta. ABC, as the smallest and weakest of the big three networks, would not be on nearly the same footing with CBS and NBC until the 1970s, when most markets of Augusta's size grew large enough to support three full network affiliates. However, fellow NBC affiliate [[WIS-TV]] in [[Columbia, South Carolina|Columbia]] provided at least grade B coverage to the South Carolina side of the market. In contrast, no full-time ABC affiliate put even a grade B signal into the area. Fuqua reasoned that if channel 6 took a primary ABC affiliation, it wouldn't have significant out-of-market competition.  Additionally, in 1966 Fuqua bought two full-time ABC affiliates, [[WTVW]] in [[Evansville, Indiana]] and KTHI-TV (now [[KVLY-TV]]) in [[Fargo, North Dakota]], and apparently wanted to get his other stations\u2014WJBF and [[KTVE]] in [[El Dorado, Arkansas]]\u2014in line with the new acquisitions. In 1969, Fuqua branched out into the movie theater business when he purchased Martin Theaters of Georgia, forerunner of [[Carmike Cinemas]]. At the time, Martin Theaters of Georgia itself also owned [[WTVM]] in [[Columbus, Georgia]], and [[WTVC]] in [[Chattanooga, Tennessee]], also ABC affiliates.  Those were added to Fuqua's portfolio.\n\nWhen WATU (channel 26, later WAGT) began operations in December 1968, conventional wisdom suggested that it would become a full NBC affiliate. However, since many Augusta viewers still didn't have UHF-capable sets, NBC allowed WJBF and WRDW-TV to continue to cherry-pick most of its stronger programs.  For its part, WJBF kept airing both the ''[[Today (American TV program)|Today Show]]'' and ''[[The Tonight Show]]'', which preempted ABC's ''[[The Dick Cavett Show]]'' among others. WATU was thus saddled with NBC's weaker programs, a major factor in the station going dark in 1970.<ref>\"One (network) to a customer.\" ''Broadcasting'', March 29, 1971, pg. 67. [http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-IDX/71-OCR/1971-03-29-BC-0068.pdf] {{dead link|date=June 2014}}</ref> When WATU returned to the air in 1974 as a full-time NBC affiliate, WJBF was forced to drop NBC programming once and for all, per an FCC order issued in 1971 that required VHF stations in markets with three or more commercial outlets to affiliate with only one network.\n\nFuqua began breaking up his business empire in 1980. His television stations were among the first assets to be sold, with WJBF and WTVM going to [[Missoula, Montana]]-based Western Broadcasting Company.<ref>[http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-IDX/80-OCR/1980-07-28-BC-OCR-Page-82.pdf]{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}[http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-IDX/80-OCR/1980-07-28-BC-OCR-Page-83.pdf \"Changing Hands.\" ''Broadcasting'', July 28, 1980, pp. 82-83]{{dead link|date=June 2014 }}</ref>, and WTVC going to the [[A. H. Belo Corporation]] of Dallas, Texas.   In 1984, Western sold its broadcast holdings to the [[Pearson Scott Foresman|SFN Companies]], then-parent of educational publisher [[Scott Foresman|Scott, Foresman and Company]].<ref>[http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-IDX/84-OCR/BC-1984-01-16-Page-0041.pdf \"Western sale.\" ''Broadcasting'', January 16, 1984, pg. 41] {{dead link|date=June 2014}}</ref> In 1986, SFN was sold to Pegasus Broadcasting, a new firm formed by members of SFN's management.<ref>[http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-IDX/86-OCR/BC-1986-07-14-Page-0066.pdf \"Changing hands.\" ''Broadcasting'', July 14, 1986, pg. 66] {{dead link|date=June 2014}}</ref> Spartan Radiocasting of [[Spartanburg, South Carolina]] purchased the station in 1992. Spartan was renamed [[Spartan Communications]] in 1995. Spartan merged with current owner [[Media General]] in 2000.\n\nWJBF replaced RTV with [[MeTV]] on digital subchannel 6.2 on September 26, 2011, as part of a groupwide affiliation agreement with Media General; the channel replaced RTV on some Media General-owned stations in other market.<ref>[http://www.tvnewscheck.com/article/2011/09/15/54029/metv-beefs-up-roster-with-10-new-stations Me-TV Beefs Up Roster With 10 New Stations] ''TVNewsCheck'', September 15, 2011.</ref>\n\n=== Augusta West, management of WAGT ===\n[[File:TV Networks in the former Barnes & Noble Augusta GA.jpg|thumb|left|The exterior of the new Television Park at Augusta West.]]\nIn October 2009, [[Schurz Communications]] announced that it would enter into joint sales and [[shared services agreement]]s with WJBF, meaning that [[WAGT (TV)|WAGT]]'s news operation and advertising sales department would be taken over by Media General. Most of WAGT's managerial staff were dismissed, and other employees were reassigned to different positions.<ref>{{cite news|last=Emerson|first=LaTina|title=WJBF, WAGT still negotiating with on-air personnel|url=http://chronicle.augusta.com/stories/2009/12/30/bus_561276.shtml|work=[[The Augusta Chronicle]]|date=December 30, 2009|accessdate=December 5, 2010}}</ref>\n\nMedia General had initially intended to move WAGT into an expanded wing of the WJBF building in downtown Augusta. Both WJBF and WAGT have had a longstanding presence in the downtown area. Channel 6's facility on Reynolds Street was built around 1956, and channel 26 moved into its Broad Street building, a converted theatre, in 1981. However, it soon became apparent that WJBF's facility could not sustain the expansion necessary to house both stations.  Media General instead chose to remodel what had been a [[big-box store]] to contain the stations. The new facility, located at the Augusta West Shopping Center in a former [[Barnes & Noble]] retail location, was opened in October 2011.<ref>{{cite news|last=Emerson|first=LaTina|title=WBBQ, other stations to move to new locations|url=http://chronicle.augusta.com/news/metro/2010-12-02/wbbq-other-stations-move-new-locations?v=1291282932|work=[[The Augusta Chronicle]]|date=December 2, 2010|accessdate=December 5, 2010}}</ref> While the two stations shared some internal services, WAGT's news operation and sales department operated autonomously from that of WJBF, and the two stations also produced competing news programming from their dedicated areas of the facility.<ref name=\"tvnc-wagtstudio\">{{cite web|title=Facility Helps Duop TVs Keep Own Identities|url=http://www.tvnewscheck.com/article/61044/facility-helps-duop-tvs-keep-own-identities|author=Arthur Greenwald|work=TVNewsCheck|publisher=NewsCheckMedia|date=July 26, 2012|accessdate=September 11, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe SSA was disbanded on February 16, 2016 after the acquisition of WAGT by [[Gray Television]], owner of [[WRDW-TV]].<ref name=\"gray-wagt\">{{cite web|title=Gray Television and WRDW News 12 Welcome WAGT NBC 26|url=http://www.wrdw.com/home/headlines/Gray-Television-and-WRDW-News-12-Welcome-WAGT-NBC-26-365796691.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160217092451/http://www.wrdw.com/home/headlines/Gray-Television-and-WRDW-News-12-Welcome-WAGT-NBC-26-365796691.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=17 February 2016|website=WRDW.com|publisher=Gray Television|accessdate=16 February 2016}}</ref> Gray accused Media General of \"[refusing] to agree to a smooth transition of personnel [from WAGT]\" and not allowing them to move along to the station's new owner, as they fell under the employment of WJBF due to the shared services agreement.<ref name=\"tvspy-blames\">{{cite web|title=Gray Blames Media General for Possible Job Losses at Augusta Station|url=http://www.adweek.com/tvspy/gray-blames-media-general-for-possible-job-losses-at-augusta-station/164035#.VsOdRLijBd0.mailto|website=TVSpy.com|accessdate=17 February 2016}}</ref> On February 26, 2016, an [[injunction]] was granted against Gray by Media General, claiming that Gray violated the SSA by unwinding it following its purchase of WAGT. The agreement was to last through 2020, and stipulated that all future owners of the station would remain subject to it.<ref name=\"chron-injunction\">{{cite news|title=Judge grants injunction halting WAGT sale|url=http://chronicle.augusta.com/news/business/2016-02-26/judge-grants-injunction-halting-wagt-sale|accessdate=February 27, 2016|work=The Augusta Chronicle|date=February 26, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Digital channels==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Channel\n! [[Video resolution|Video]]\n! [[Aspect ratio|Aspect]]\n! PSIP short name\n! Programming\n|-\n| 6.1 || [[1080i]] || rowspan=\"3\"|[[16:9]] || WJBF-HD || Main WJBF programming / [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] \n|-\n| 6.2 || [[720p]] || MeTV || [[MeTV]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www2.wjbf.com/entertainment/on_wjbf_tv/ |title=WJBF website TV listings |access-date=June 30, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110609075423/http://www2.wjbf.com/entertainment/on_wjbf_tv/ |archive-date=June 9, 2011 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n|-\n| 6.3 || rowspan=\"2\"|[[480i]] || ION || [[Ion Television]]\n|-\n| 6.4 || [[4:3]] || || [[Court TV Mystery]]\n|}\n\n==Local programming==\nSince 1954, WJBF has produced and aired the Sunday morning [[gospel music]] program ''Parade of Quartets'', one of the longest-running local programs of any kind on American television. The program has been a showcase for regionally and nationally known African-American gospel performers, and has also featured appearances from political and social figures. Augusta native [[James Brown]], [[Shirley Caesar]], [[Al Green]], the [[Mighty Clouds of Joy]], [[Dorothy Norwood]] and [[Jesse Jackson]] are among those who have appeared on the program.\n\nThe station also produces an [[urban music]] video program, ''Power Hitz'', which airs on Sunday evenings. ''Power Hitz'' has been on the air since 2001.<ref>{{cite news|last=DeMao|first=Alisa|title=Radio personalities add camera to mike|url=http://chronicle.augusta.com/stories/2001/09/13/ent_319380.shtml|work=[[The Augusta Chronicle]]|date=September 13, 2001|accessdate=December 5, 2010}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1954 until 1992, WJBF produced and aired a Sunday afternoon [[Southern gospel]] program featuring the locally based [[The Lewis Family]], known as the \"First Family of Bluegrass Gospel,\" that was seen in other markets via [[broadcast syndication|syndication]]. After the weekly series ended, WJBF continued to produce and air a yearly [[Christmas]] special until the group's retirement in 2009.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://thelewisfamilymusic.com|title=Home Page|website=thelewisfamilymusic|language=en-US|access-date=2018-07-06}}</ref>\n\n==News operation==\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Wjbf open 2010.png|thumb|right|The WJBF news open seen nightly at 6.{{deletable image-caption|Thursday, 31 March 2016}}]] -->\nAppropriately for being the first television station in the area, WJBF has led the ratings for most of its history, with rival WRDW-TV usually the runner-up. In recent years, WJBF and WRDW-TV had usually traded first and second place, while WAGT almost always placed third.\n\nIn the 1980s, its newscasts were branded ''[[NewsWatch (branding)|NewsWatch]] 6''. After being acquired by Spartan Radiocasting in 1992, WJBF and some other stations acquired by the company changed their branding to ''NewsChannel''. This station and most of its sister affiliates still use this branding today after being acquired by Media General. However, long after Spartan bought the station, WJBF retained the \"groovy 6\" logo it had used in one form or another since the late 1970s. This changed in 2002, when it adopted the \"arc\" logo used by most Media General stations.\n\nIn the 1990s, WJBF reached an agreement with the [[Augusta Mall]] to run a [[closed-circuit television|closed-circuit]] \"Mall TV\" feed on television screens throughout the mall featuring the day's news and coverage of some local special events. WJBF operated this service until the late-1990s. They also had a local agreement with Comcast to air a rebroadcast of the 6 p.m. show on the cable provider's channel 66. This arrangement ended in 2004 with the launch of a nightly 10 o'clock newscast on [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] affiliate [[WFXG]] (channel 54). The production uses different graphics and duratrans concealing the WJBF logos. The launch came after its studios were renovated.\n\nIn December 2009, WAGT and WJBF partnered under a shared services agreement, with WJBF producing WAGT's news, sales, and other programming. Schurz Communications still owns WAGT in part. Current WJBF reporter Paige Tucker is the face of WAGT's 6, 7, and 11pm newscasts.\n\nOn October 17, 2011, WJBF launched local newscasts in high definition starting with the morning newscast. It is the third station in the area to do so behind WFXG and WRDW-TV.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|https://www.wjbf.com/}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20101127154038/http://paradeofquartets.com/main/ ''Parade of Quartets'' website]\n*{{TVQ|WJBF}}\n\n{{Augusta TV}}\n{{ABC Georgia}}\n{{NXST TV}}\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2012}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wjbf}}\n[[Category:ABC network affiliates]]\n[[Category:Television stations in Augusta, Georgia|JBF]]\n[[Category:Television channels and stations established in 1953]]\n[[Category:1953 establishments in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:MeTV affiliates]]\n[[Category:Ion Television subchannel-only affiliates]]\n[[Category:Court TV Mystery affiliates]]\n[[Category:Prime Time Entertainment Network]]\n[[Category:Nexstar Media Group]]\n[[Category:Atlantic Coast Conference broadcasters]]\n", "name_user": "Armando619", "label": "safe", "comment": "update page and information", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WJBF"}
